If you're rich enough to make use of the perks after paying the $550 fee you could THEORETICALLY derive some real value, but it's probably still a bad financial decision.

Their points are generally worth a penny and usually less. In order to actually use most of their benefits at hotels the cardholder needs to book directly through the hotel and likely pay the rack rate.

As a reward, the cardholder gets points through the hotel chain which are again of modest value and perks of modest value. Did I mention that you pay the rack rate or nearly the rack rate for this privilege?
The selling point seems to be signaling to service workers and onlookers that the cardholder has the rich person card that is accepted in fewer US locations than Visa and Mastercard.

Rich Fairbanks is kind of my contra. He's been coasting on cap one being a specialty lender with a bank cost of funds for a long time. $cof was at one point was a specialty lender that bought a bank so they could could begin to originate auto loans

their entire moat has been based on making the kinds of loans that a specialty finance co would generally make, but they pick off the best customers through pricing and a better cost of funds. the environment has now totally changed

digital banking and the internet is making retail banking extremely competitive - it's very easy for the consumer to actively price shop for the best interest rates on everything. it used to be that cap one was the obvious choice for deposits for a good CD rate but not anymore

the essential equation behind making loan is roa = apr - cof - company expenses - loss. you always price to roa. but the way to grow your loan book is by beating your competition on APR. all else equal, being better on cof and predicting losses is how you do that

reiterating - structurally, you're beating your competition on either cost of funds (see: bank cof v. non bank cof ) or loss expectation is what leads to a competitive advantage (no one has a structural advantage here on losses except MAYBE $jpm $wfc).

in the cost of funds part of their equation, digital banking is getting extremely competitive in a rising rate environment. ally, finn, marcus, etc. are here to stay and GSIBs are meaningfully competing for deposits that would usually go to cap one

cap one generally competes in credit card, auto, and now corporate finance. (mortage didn't work out because they couldn't competitively price on the cof against more regular banks). in a rising rate environment their COF moat is eroding.

in auto, $ally has figured this out, and they're making a strong, meaningful push to be the next cap one. $wfc is signaling they're going to compete in auto again after taking their foot of the pedal past couple years
in corporate finance, they're basically a bdc and they don't have the human capital/expertise to compete with actual bdcs.
idk, i'm just drunk rambling. please disagree with me

Adding a couple more thoughts to my thread after a great convo with @WallStFlex tonight. I feel like in trading its better to specialize in one area and become a master at your craft. Instead of being a jack of all trades,  master of none. Or else you just half ass everything.

You don't see plumbers doing electrical work. Or carpenters installing a toilet. Or electricians hanging drywall. (My italian construction side coming out to play @WallStFlex ). When you build a house you hire all the trades separately and everyone does their own job.

So why as traders are we jumping around from stock to stock scanning 1000 stocks a night and trying to trade them without even learning how they trade. Every stock has its own personality. They all ebb and flow differently. Spreads and liquidity are different in every stock.

When business gets quiet you don't see an electrician start bidding on a job to run copper pipes. He waits until business picks up and takes advantage of it and takes on more jobs and works longer hours when business is good.

Same thing in trading. We sit on our hands til the opportunity strikes. Then you take advantage when volatility picks back up. You don't wander over and trade a stock you've never traded before, just to get some action and feel the rush. Thats addiction.

Patterns may work in one stock, but the same pattern may not work in another stock. There is a TON of turdy stocks out there that suck you in with a fancy pattern from the textbooks and then pull the rug on you. I'll get into the fallacy of patterns and why they dont work soon.

If you look at many hedge funds they have traders who's only job is to trade one asset. Look it up. They have /es traders. They have oil traders. They have gold traders. They have spx options traders. They all specialize in one area. Research it I'm not lying.

So how come we as retail amateur traders learning from textbooks and some online articles think we can jump in the ring with Muhammed Ali and trade 50 different stocks properly just because they popped up on our scanners with a pattern we read about in a book?
